{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774293472,"nonce":"TCTSfRiLiwwo0L93owr6UOpFdsY=","title":"GRU laziness and architecture choice for robust control","message":"## Summary\n\nGRU update gates allow a \"just maintain bias\" shortcut: low update gate = ignore new input, keep hidden state constant. This means the network can learn to scale its output with SISU (adaptive gain scheduling) without genuinely changing its feedback dynamics. If the Jacobian eigenvalue test shows PAI-ASF only shifts the fixed point without changing eigenvalue magnitudes/angles, the network is being lazy.\n\n## Diagnostic\n\nCompute the recurrent Jacobian dh_{t+1}/dh_t at steady state across SISU levels. Under genuine robustness, eigenvalue structure should change with SISU (tighter decay, higher frequency — indicating increased feedback gain). Under laziness, only the fixed point location shifts (bias change, same dynamics).\n\nThis test is already partially implemented in fps_steady.py (eigenvalue analysis). Needs to be explicitly compared across SISU levels with this framing.\n\n## Mitigations Within GRU Architecture\n\n1. **Sensitivity penalty in loss**: Evaluate same trial with/without a small probe perturbation, penalize the difference in tracking error. Forces genuine perturbation rejection rather than trajectory biasing. Cost: 2 forward passes per training trial.\n\n2. **SISU-scaled noise**: Make motor noise or feedback noise scale with SISU during training. At high beta, noisier system forces tighter feedback loops (actual gain increase). Cheap to implement, biologically plausible.\n\n3. **Adversarial training (APT)**: Structurally prevents laziness because the adversary exploits any strategy that doesn't genuinely increase robustness. See companion issue on APT/CVaR.\n\n4. **Frozen update gate ablation**: Fix the GRU update gate at a high value (always integrate new input) and retrain. If this produces better robustness signatures, the gating was the problem.\n\n## Architecture Alternatives\n\n- **Vanilla RNN** (no gating): Forces active processing of every input. Less stable to train but eliminates the \"maintain bias\" shortcut. Loses selective memory, which might actually be desirable if memory enables adaptation rather than robustness.\n\n- **Linear recurrent networks** (S4/S5 style): Fixed dynamics with learnable parameters. Eigenvalue structure more interpretable and harder to hack with gating. May be too constrained for this task.\n\n- **LSTM**: Similar gating concerns as GRU but with separate forget/input gates. Not expected to help with the laziness problem.\n\n## Note\n\nThe laziness problem is not GRU-specific — it's a property of any architecture trained with expected-cost backprop. The GRU's update gate just makes it especially easy. Loss-function fixes should be tried first; architecture changes are the fallback.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}